1
00:00:00,170 --> 00:00:06,140
In this video we are going to explain IRB architecture with the pipelines and extensibility.

2
00:00:06,260 --> 00:00:10,160
So here you can see the IRB architecture with pipelines.

3
00:00:10,160 --> 00:00:15,200
And we will start with the ASP.Net core front end and Http client backends.

4
00:00:15,380 --> 00:00:18,500
We are leveraging ASP.Net core for its front end.

5
00:00:18,530 --> 00:00:23,420
Handling the incoming requests and Http client for communication with back end services.

6
00:00:23,450 --> 00:00:29,930
It integrates seamlessly into ASP.Net core infrastructure, working as a middleware that can be combined

7
00:00:29,930 --> 00:00:32,450
with other components like API calls.

8
00:00:32,600 --> 00:00:35,600
And also it includes configuration and route loadings.

9
00:00:35,630 --> 00:00:41,900
Routes are loaded from the configuration sources, with ASP.Net Json file being the default.

10
00:00:41,930 --> 00:00:48,350
These routes are then loaded into ASP.Net route table, enabling the IRB to match incoming requests

11
00:00:48,350 --> 00:00:49,880
to specific routes.

12
00:00:49,910 --> 00:00:56,030
And also we can define routes to cluster mapping after receiving a request that match a route.

13
00:00:56,060 --> 00:00:58,430
Your maps this route to a cluster.

14
00:00:58,430 --> 00:01:02,810
Determining the potential destination or back end services for the request.

15
00:01:02,810 --> 00:01:07,580
And after that we can say dynamic configuration via config provider model.

16
00:01:07,790 --> 00:01:13,850
IRB allows for dynamic configuration through a config provider model, enabling runtime changes and

17
00:01:13,850 --> 00:01:19,700
adjustments based on various factors like back end, server status or application requirements, and

18
00:01:19,700 --> 00:01:24,470
also IRB provide session affinity and load balancing during the proxy process.

19
00:01:24,590 --> 00:01:31,280
IRB can maintain session affinity cookie sessions, ensuring that requests from a particular client

20
00:01:31,280 --> 00:01:35,570
are consistently routed to the same server for load balancing.

21
00:01:35,600 --> 00:01:41,990
IRB employs algorithms like power of Two choices, which select two random destinations and chooses

22
00:01:41,990 --> 00:01:43,820
the least loaded among them.

23
00:01:44,030 --> 00:01:46,880
And also this will be providing health checks.

24
00:01:46,910 --> 00:01:49,910
IRB support both active and passive health checks.

25
00:01:49,940 --> 00:01:55,550
Active health checks regularly ping configured endpoints in back end services to assess their health.

26
00:01:55,550 --> 00:02:01,310
Passive health checks observed the response codes from the back end services as traffic is forwarded,

27
00:02:01,310 --> 00:02:05,390
marking servers as unhealthy based on certain criterias.

28
00:02:05,570 --> 00:02:09,590
And also we can say request and response processing during this process.

29
00:02:09,620 --> 00:02:14,780
IRB can transform requests by modifying URLs, headers, and other attributes.

30
00:02:14,780 --> 00:02:18,770
It typically avoids modifying the body to maintain performance.

31
00:02:18,770 --> 00:02:22,790
The transformed request is then forwarded to selected back end server.

32
00:02:22,790 --> 00:02:25,220
And this is the pipeline of the process.

33
00:02:25,220 --> 00:02:28,940
And we can also add the pipeline modularization and extensibility.

34
00:02:29,120 --> 00:02:33,590
IRB also is designed as a pipeline, with each step being a module.

35
00:02:33,590 --> 00:02:36,350
You can see for these steps as a module.

36
00:02:36,350 --> 00:02:42,500
Every module like route matching, load balancing, health checks, request transforms and so on can

37
00:02:42,500 --> 00:02:45,590
be customized or replaced with custom implementation.

38
00:02:45,590 --> 00:02:51,770
So this modular architecture provide immense flexibility to tailored IRB to specific requirements.

39
00:02:52,010 --> 00:02:55,100
And here you can see the extensibility points of the IRB.

40
00:02:55,130 --> 00:02:58,310
IRB is highly extensible using the C sharp.

41
00:02:58,310 --> 00:03:03,980
It allows you to customize almost every aspects of the request processing and forwarding.

42
00:03:04,010 --> 00:03:10,490
Developers can extend or replace components of the IRB pipeline to seat specific requirements, and

43
00:03:10,490 --> 00:03:15,620
we can say that we can develop our custom configurations, and custom configurations can be written

44
00:03:15,620 --> 00:03:16,280
in C sharp.

45
00:03:16,280 --> 00:03:20,900
For more complex scenarios where Json based configurations are not sufficient.

46
00:03:20,900 --> 00:03:26,930
This provides developers with the flexibility to program complex logic into their proxy behaviors.

